'''Mark Garry Hammett''' (born [[13 July]] [[1972]] in [[Christchurch]]) is a [[rugby union]] [[coach]], and former [[New Zealand]] rugby union player. Hammett played provincial rugby for [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]], as [[Rugby union positions#2. Hooker|Hooker]], between 1992 and 2002. When the [[Crusaders]] franchise was formed for the [[Super 12]] in 1996, Hammett was contracted, becoming a founding player. He continued to play for the Crusaders until 2003; winning four championships in the process. Hammett first played for the [[All Blacks]] in 1999, and played until his retirement following the [[2003 Rugby World Cup]]. Hammett represented Canterbury 76 times, the Crusaders 81 times, and the All Blacks 30 times (including 29 [[Test match|Tests]]). After retiring from playing, Hammett began coaching, he worked as a forwards advisor for both the Crusaders and Canterbury in 2006. He was appointed to succeed Vern Cotter as assitant coach at the Crusaders for the 2007 season.

==Background==


==Playing career==
Hammett first represented New Zealand when he was selected for New Zealand Under 17 in 1989.<ref name="ABProfile">{{cite web| url=http://stats.allblacks.com/Profile.asp?ABID=353 |title= 	   	
Mark Hammett |publisher=allblacks.com |accessdate=2007-01-26}}</ref> He then captained the Under 19 team in 1991, before making his first appearance for Canterbury in 1992. Although his one game for Canterbury in 1992 was as a replacement, he played seven games the following season.<ref name="ABProfile"/> Playing as hooker, he was played mainly as backup to Matt Sexton in 1993, however by 1994 they were both sharing the role. By 1995, Hammett was playing more games then Sexton.<ref name="ABProfile"/>

Rugby turned professional in 1995, and in 1996 the Canterbury Crusaders (now called the ''Crusaders'') franchise was established. Hammett became a founding member of the side, as they struggled to last place in the inaugural Super 12.<ref name="CrusadersProfile">{{cite web| url=http://www.crfu.co.nz/main/index.cfm/1,393,1560,html/Mark-Hammett-Assistant-Coach |title=Mark Hammett - Assistant Coach |publisher=crfu.co.nz |accessdate=2007-01-26}}</ref><ref name="Lassen1996">{{cite web| url=http://www.lassen.co.nz/s14tab.php#hrh |title=Super 14 Tables |publisher=lassen.co.nz |accessdate=2007-01-26}}</ref> The 1997 season went better for Hammett; the Crusaders finished sixth, and the Canterbury team won the [[National Provincial Championship]] by beating [[Counties Manukau Rugby Union|Counties]] (NPC) in the final.<ref name="Lassen1996"/> Hammett was receiving more and more game time, and participated in the NPC final as a replacement.<ref name="ABProfile"/>

Hammett started regularly for both Canterbury, and the Crusaders in 1998. With the latter he won his first Super 12 title with the Crusaders. The 1998 Super 12 final was played against the [[Blues (Super rugby franchise)|Blues]] at Eden Park, Hammett said of the match "If we'd been polled in that week, and had to give an honest answer, most of the boys, deep down, would probably have thought that the Blues would beat us."<ref name="McIlraith84">McIlraith (205), pg 84.</ref> Despite this, the Crusaders won 20-13 against the reining champions.<ref name="McIlraith85">McIlraith (2005), pg 85.</ref> Hammett was rewarded with a New Zealand trial, where he captained his team.<ref name="ABProfile"/> He was eventually selected for New Zealand A, and played against [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]].<ref name="ABProfile"/>

